and 13 years.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Well, I enjoyed,

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
so I had no idea when I started forming this presentation

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
that Jeremy was going to be one of the keynote speakers.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
But I really enjoyed listening to JJ and Jeremy

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
do this thing they called a two-way AMA,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
which I didn't know what that's called.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
I've been calling it having a conversation,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
and I'm just not really cool, right?

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
So I learned that this is called a two-way AMA,

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
and they recorded their two-way AMA,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.000
and it's on YouTube, and it's really fantastic.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.000
And I was listening to this

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
as I was driving from my parents' house

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
to Nashville, Tennessee,

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.000
and if my family hadn't been with me,

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:55.000
I would have pulled over to the side of the road

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
because I was listening to just the audio on my iPhone,

00:05:58.000 --> 00:05:59.000
and I would have pulled over to the side of the road

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:00.000
and made notes.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:01.000
So I ended up listening to it

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
and going back and listening to it again.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And one of the things that jumped out is

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
they made the comment of if you think about

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
how you help both new users ramp into things

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.000
and make experienced users productive,

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:17.000
you provide these abstractions,

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.000
and there's a dial of how leaky

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
you want the abstraction to be.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
Now, a bunch of us who've been around software,

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.000
maybe worked in software engineering,

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
but definitely talked about to software engineers,

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:34.000
know this idea of abstractions and leaky abstractions.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:35.000
In this community,

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.000
a bunch of us come through clinical sciences

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.000
or we come through other fields

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
that aren't computation first,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
and I was thinking this term is really powerful,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
both abstractions and the idea of an abstraction leaking.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
These are really important concepts

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
that I think we should more widely ingest.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
So when Headley contacted me and said,

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:55.000
hey, you want a keynote?

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:59.000
I'm like, yeah, what's themes or whatever?

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:00.000
And he's basically like,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
I don't know, you use Python and R,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
maybe like some, I don't know,

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
do whatever you're thinking about, right?

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Well, it just happened, I was thinking about this,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
and this has been one of the things

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
I've been thinking about with my team

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:13.000
and the people I work with,

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.000
is how do we talk explicitly about abstractions,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
leaky abstractions, and how we deal with those leaks?

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
So let's talk a little bit about abstractions

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:23.000
and leaky abstractions.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
So first thing I did was go back,

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:28.000
I thought I knew where this came from,

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:31.000
and I confirmed that while the term leaky abstraction

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.000
was around in the zeitgeist,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:37.000
it really didn't get traction in the tech community

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:41.000
until Joel Spolsky wrote this blog post

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:43.000
over 20 years ago,

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:46.000
and he calls it the law of leaky abstractions,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:49.000
and the law is all non-trivial abstractions

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
to some degree are leaky.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And what he means by that is an abstraction failure,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
sometimes a little, sometimes a lot,

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:57.000
there's leakage, things go wrong,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
it happens all over the place

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
when you have abstractions, right?

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.000
So it means that you have this thing you're relating to,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:07.000
it's abstracted away so you have an interface,

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.000
an API, a calling to a function,

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
and you interface with it in a way

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
and it doesn't do what you expect.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:17.000
That's a leak.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.000
So the question becomes, what do you do?

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
So you've got, if you want to be a master

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
of any abstraction, not just a user,

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
but a master of the abstraction,

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
you have to understand what's under the abstraction.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.000
Now that's the only way you can truly debug

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.000
or truly understand an abstraction

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
is to understand at least one layer beyond.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
And I did a lot of research trying to figure out

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.000
who originally said this concept of

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
you've got to understand one abstraction below

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:47.000
in order to be proficient and debug one abstraction,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
and everything I found was sort of like

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:50.000
everybody just knows that.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
Like nobody attributes that thought to anyone,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:55.000
it's just in the zeitgeist that that is reality,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
so I guess it's like an axiom.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.000
So when we think about abstraction,

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.000
I want to expand what I mean,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
because many of you are probably thinking

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:04.000
something like this,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.000
and I just like Googled computing abstraction, right?

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:09.000
Where we have at the high level,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
you have like a high level language

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:13.000
or an application,

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:16.000
and then it goes through an assembly language program

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
and the assembler turns it into machine code,

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:20.000
and then it, like actually,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
then there's a bunch of hardware abstractions,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:25.000
and then an actual calculation gets done

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:26.000
inside the hardware of the machine.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
That's how we often think about abstractions.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:33.000
I want to expand that for the purpose of this conversation,

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
because there's also organizational abstractions.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:37.000
So if you think of an abstraction as

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.000
we've got some set of directives we're passing down,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
and we kind of don't care specifically

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
how things get done in the next layer,

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.000
we just want the next layer to do something,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:55.000
well that's not unlike organizational structures.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
I come from corporate America, right?

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:58.000
So I think,

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
but this generally concept applies to your nonprofit

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
or your software company

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
or even your civic organization.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.000
At some level,

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
we have a board of directors or some committee,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
and they pass down directives and priorities

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
to the executive management.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.000
The executive management makes a bunch of choices

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
and then passes things down to department heads

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:21.000
who pass it to team leads,

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
who pass it to team contributors,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:24.000
and if we continue to think about this,

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
they then pass those on to computers in some way, right?

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Like they pass in because they use applications

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
or they use high-level coding languages or something,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
and then all that other stuff from the slide before

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
happens underneath this.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
It's abstractions all the way down, right?

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:43.000
There's the title of my talk.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
So why though,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:51.000
like why do we need these abstractions all the way down?

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
Wouldn't it be easier if we just had,

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
like I grew up on a farm,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
and the great thing about farming is

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
you have to do everything because you don't have staff.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.000
The worst thing about farming is

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
you have to do everything because you don't have staff, right?

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
So you become a master of every level of abstraction

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:09.000
until you get in over your head

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
and you have to have John Deere

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
repair some piece of machinery or something, right?

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:15.000
But you become,

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
all the way up and down the levels of abstraction,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
you become at least proficient.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
It's been hard for me to get used to organizations

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:25.000
that didn't expect me to run up and down the stack, right?

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
Because I want to run up and down all the abstractions.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
Well, the reason we can't always do that

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.000
was really articulated back in the 50s by Herbert Simon.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
He's an economist, I'm an economist,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
so I've got to get economists in here.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
He had this article in 1957 called

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
Administrative Behavior,

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
A Study of Decision-Making Processes

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
in Administrative Organizations,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
and he coined the phrase bounded rationality,

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:58.000
which I TLDR as head trunk only hold so much junk,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
which Gary Lawson captured in this cartoon

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
where it says, Mr. Osborne, may I be excused?

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
My brain is full.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.000
We can only handle so many levels of abstraction

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
and so many pieces of the stack

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
before our brain overflows,

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.000
and we can't make sense of all the pieces.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
And so we build these interfaces,

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
and even if we are the person

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
traversing the levels of abstraction,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
we would like to interface with different pieces of them

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
and not think about what happens below them,

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
even if we wrote what's below them,

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
because it means when we're problem-solving here,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:38.000
we don't have to think about how the read-write

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
is happening on the database.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:45.000
That just magically happens behind an abstract interface,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
and we don't have to think about it,

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
and it allows us to work at the problem-solving level

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
that's appropriate for what we're trying to accomplish.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
That seems to make a lot of sense, right, intuitively?

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
So let's talk a little bit about what abstractions are for

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
and what they are not for.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
So one thing I want to point out that they're not for

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
is they're not for gatekeeping,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
and I see this being done a lot, right?

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
You're not a real data scientist unless you, you know,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:17.000
PyTorch or deep learning or whatever.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
Those are all different abstractions, different tools,

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
that are used in certain places to solve certain problems.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
Those may not be your problems.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
Then you don't need to know that abstraction.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
You don't need to be a master of that abstraction.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
You don't need to be one layer below,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
and I watch a lot of early learners

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.000
run around learning abstractions, learning tools,

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
because they feel like if they don't know this tool,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
they're not a real whatever-it-is-they-think-they-want-to-be.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:49.000
That's really toxic, because you'll wear yourself out

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:52.000
because this guy has already said

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.000
you can't fit it all in your head in a really useful way.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
So don't let the learning of abstractions be like,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.000
oh, once I accumulate a big enough toolbox of these abstractions,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
then I'm a real whatever.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
That's just gatekeeping, and cut that out.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:14.000
You don't even have to know all the abstractions you use deeply.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
But you do need to know your limits.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.000
So know which abstractions you really understand.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.000
Recognize when you're up against an abstraction that you don't grok,

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
so you don't understand the abstraction.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
It's a breakpoint.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
You're like, I don't really understand what's going on beyond here.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
At that point, you have a choice.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
You can either learn that abstraction,

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
learn what's really going on beyond it,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
so that you can deeply understand it,

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.000
or you can partner with someone who's an expert there.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:47.000
Partnership and pairing with someone else

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
and working with someone else is always an option.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
It may be harder in some organizations than others,

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
especially if you're the only person on the data science team.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:58.000
You may feel some pressure to learn those abstractions,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
and that may be the right choice.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
But if you're in a larger organization,

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.000
and someone else in the organization is a master of that abstraction,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
you may not need to become the expert on database indexing.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.000
Contact Kara. She seems to know a lot about it.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:19.000
And we have to choose, make that choice.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
Now, what I see happen a lot

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:27.000
is people blame an abstraction for problems when they bump up against it.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:28.000
And often the problem is,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
they don't understand what the abstraction is doing.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:33.000
Now, that may be a leaky abstraction,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:34.000
but still, it's like,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
okay, my dashboard doesn't refresh fast enough.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
My database has a problem.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:44.000
I had literally this one within the last year.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
And I worked with the Power BI developer,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:51.000
and we discovered that when using direct query in Power BI,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
which is how you access any database

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
that isn't the one that's built into Power BI,

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.000
it issues all the queries in series

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.000
and will not issue them in parallel.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
So the dashboard had, you know, 13 queries

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:07.000
that all took three seconds.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
They could have been run in parallel,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
and the whole thing refreshed in three seconds.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
Instead, it took 13 times 30,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:15.000
because it was running them in serial.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:19.000
And the analyst had thought, oh, this database is crap.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:20.000
And I'm like, actually,

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:24.000
Microsoft is shunting you into buying more cloud storage

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
so you can shove your data into their platform

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
instead of letting you use your own perfectly good database

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:31.000
because they force your connection

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
to issue queries in serial.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And I'm like, that's broken, right?

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
That's not a leaky abstraction by accident.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
That's a leaky abstraction by sales, right?

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
And that should make anybody that runs into that one angry.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
And it made me angry.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:47.000
And I'm like, we've got to get other tools.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:48.000
This is ridiculous.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Like, we're being manipulated.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:51.000
We're being played.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:52.000
And my analyst didn't know it, right?

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
Because he didn't really understand that abstraction.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
He didn't realize how to go into the database,

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.000
get the logs,

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
and see that they were happening in serial.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
But he does now, right?

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
But that's an example of don't blame the abstraction.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
Understand the abstraction.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:07.000
Understand what's going on.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:10.000
And then decide what you want to do with that information.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
So I would, if I did anything

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
where I dabble with, like, computer sciencey concepts

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:20.000
and I don't quote Edgar Dijkstra here,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:21.000
I would probably be remiss.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:25.000
So he has this kind of great quote

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:26.000
that says,

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
Programming, when stripped of all its

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
circumstantial irrelevancies,

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
boils down to no more and no less

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
than very effective thinking

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.000
so as to avoid unmastered complexity

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
to very vigorous separations

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
of your many different concerns.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.000
Right?

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.000
And the TLDR is,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
constrain complexity and separate concerns.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
That's what we're trying to do with abstractions.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
And that's what you should be doing

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:51.000
when you're writing functions

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
inside your in-house libraries.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Your first priority should be,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
how do we make it less complex?

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
How do we separate concerns?

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.000
And that's that,

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:00.000
even if you understand

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:01.000
and you built the pieces

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
that are under certain abstractions,

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
if you can separate those from your thinking

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
while you think about this piece of the problem,

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
you've got less of a sandcastle in your head

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:12.000
to build the tools

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
and do the analysis you want to deal with

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:17.000
because you've got a lot of the complexity pushed away

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
and you know that if you have a certain problem,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.000
which piece of complexity

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
you then need to go look at.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
It's not all commingled together.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:25.000
So that's a really good concept

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.000
and that was, you know,

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:29.000
he wrote that down in 1975.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
And I'm not sure we've done a really good job

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:32.000
embracing that.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.000
I know I haven't.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
So, let's do a fun example

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
about thinking about abstractions.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Anybody in here an intellectual engineer?

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:44.000
Oh, more than I expected.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:45.000
I'm going to ask you guys, like,

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:46.000
not to yell at me.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
Like, just stick with me.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:49.000
Just stick with me.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.000
It's a thought exercise.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:54.000
Don't rush the stage here.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
Electricity is a fundamental abstraction for computing,

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:58.000
obviously, right?

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
We know this is all powered by electricity.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
We know, like,

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
we've got gigabit switches in our office,

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:09.000
so that's a billion bits of information a second.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
There's a bunch of wires

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
and we don't really know how that works,

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
but it's got to be at least going, like,

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:19.000
millions of ups and downs of voltage a second, right?

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
Inside your gigabit switch.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:22.000
That little light blinks fast, right?

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
It feels like something like that.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:25.000
And so, like,

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:29.000
how fast do the electrons flow in our wires?

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:30.000
So, just think about this for a minute.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
Don't yell an answer.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:33.000
How fast do they go?

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.000
And I'm like, well, okay,

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
well, we're flipping the little bits up and down,

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
you know, a million times a second or more,

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.000
maybe a billion in the wire,

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
some big number.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:43.000
That's really fast.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:44.000
That's a lot of,

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:45.000
that's got to be moving fast

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.000
to turn it on and turn it off that fast.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
It feels really fast, you know.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
I don't open the refrigerator door and it's dusk.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:54.000
It's always, you know, light straight on.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
When I was in middle school,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
they showed me illustrations that look like this,

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:01.000
and I think the red balls are the electrons, right?

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.000
So, the battery forces the electrons through,

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:07.000
so those things must be going really fast.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
You know, and then the next year,

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
the teacher did this diagram

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:15.000
and likened electric current flow to, like, water flow,

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:19.000
and, you know, resistor was like a restriction on the pipe,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:21.000
and we got that,

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
and that was really helpful,

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
so this all kind of points me to,

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
this stuff's going, like, really fast.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
We're probably going near speed of light,

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.000
but it can't be the speed of light.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:34.000
It's, you know, there's some resistance from the wire,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
and that's why wires get hot,

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
but it can't be too much

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
because they get really hot all the time,

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
and they don't, so I don't know.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
We're probably pushing the speed of light

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
inside these wires, right?

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:50.000
Yeah, no, it's 8 centimeters an hour at 1 watt.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
What?

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
Right, okay, who was surprised by that number?

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
Like, it kind of defied your intuition.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
The ones with your hands down,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
you guys are, like, smarter than me,

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
and I'm glad you're here

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
because I want to know smart people.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:06.000
The problem is

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.000
we conflate electromagnetic fields

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.000
with electron movement,

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:14.000
so the electromagnetic field moves really fast.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.000
The actual electrons move quite slow,

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
so in an AC wire,

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
when you're, you know, drying your hair,

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
it's something like this.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.000
That's the speed of the actual electrons

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
moving through the wire,

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
which kind of blows a lot of people's intuition

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:31.000
when they learned with these metaphors,

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.000
like I showed you on the previous slide.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
If anybody finds this interesting

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
and would like to go read more,

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
oh, by the way, if you want to take pictures

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.000
of my slides or anything, that's great.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:43.000
Knock yourself out.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.000
At the end, there's a QR code that'll take you

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
to GitHub repo that has the whole slide in there,

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
so don't feel like you've got to capture

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
the links or anything.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
But this is a link to a YouTube video

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
that explains this whole thing,

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.000
and it's really interesting, I found.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
But why do many of us not know this, right?

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
Because we use electronics en masse

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
every day to solve all our problems.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:07.000
Well, the reason we don't know this

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:09.000
is it doesn't matter.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.000
And not that it doesn't matter

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.000
that we don't know it.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.000
It doesn't matter.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.000
It doesn't change anything.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:19.000
There's absolutely nothing you ever know

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:21.000
where the movement of the electron matters.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.000
That abstraction never leaks.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:25.000
We never are diagnosing a problem,

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
and we're like,

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:29.000
I finally get the answer.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:31.000
It's because I thought the electrons

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:33.000
were moving fast,

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:35.000
and they're actually moving slow.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:37.000
That's never the problem we have,

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.000
because this abstraction just doesn't leak.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.000
Now, there's a whole genre

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:43.000
of YouTube videos and clickbait

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:45.000
that are basically like this.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:47.000
They surprise you

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
with some piece of information

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:51.000
you didn't know about something

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.000
that you interact with all the time,

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.000
and sometimes they're absolutely full of crap.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.000
Because we like this

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
because it's surprising,

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
because it's like a dopamine drop

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.000
when we're surprised by information.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:07.000
And at some point, though,

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
it doesn't matter.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:11.000
So, you know,

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:13.000
to understand abstraction,

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:15.000
we build these mental models.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:17.000
We make metaphors

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:19.000
like my water flow

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:21.000
or my electrons being elevated

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:23.000
and moved and dropping.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Often they're wrong metaphors,

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.000
and sometimes that doesn't matter

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.000
because they allow us to understand

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.000
the thing well enough to use it.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
So I do my own, like,

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
home electrical wiring.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:37.000
I'm rewiring.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.000
I redid my Jeep wiring.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.000
I'm doing a trailer now.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
I use computers.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:45.000
I've got a desk with, you know,

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:47.000
power supply on it

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.000
for testing Arduinos

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:51.000
and controlling, you know,

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.000
actuators with Arduinos

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:55.000
and Raspberry Pis,

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:57.000
and I understood how electrons flow through a wire.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:59.000
So my metaphor was

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:01.000
good enough, even though

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.000
it was technically wrong.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:05.000
Well,

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:07.000
what if our mental model is wrong

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
and it does matter?

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.000
Because, you know,

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:13.000
it's not a universal case that it doesn't matter.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
So, buckle up.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.000
Let's talk about

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:19.000
floating-point math.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
This is my favorite leaky abstraction.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.000
And by the way, I'm only going to have

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.000
two slides with code, and they're both Python

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.000
because we've got a big community.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:29.000
We're a very open tent.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:31.000
You know, if you took,

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:33.000
you know, grade school math,

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:35.000
everyone in here did,

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:37.000
at some point, the teacher,

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:39.000
and if they were very creative,

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:41.000
they did a pretty slide like this one

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
to explain the associative

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:45.000
property of addition

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.000
where it doesn't matter how you group

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:49.000
the things you're adding,

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:51.000
you get the same answer.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:53.000
Very young. And this is how addition

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
and multiplication work.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:57.000
And, you know, I think we all saw

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:59.000
something like this. I stole this slide

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:01.000
literally from, you know, a middle school

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:03.000
review online.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:05.000
But, we come into

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:07.000
Python, and we go, okay, well,

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.000
we got these numbers. They're real numbers.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
They're on the number line, right?

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.000
We're going to take 1.11, add 2.22,

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:15.000
and then we're going to add 3.33,

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:17.000
and we're going to group them a little

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.000
different, and they are not

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
the same.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
And the reason

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.000
they are not the same

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:27.000
is floating point addition

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:29.000
and multiplication are not

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:31.000
associative.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:33.000
And the reason why is illustrated

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:35.000
when I format the

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:37.000
print on these to show

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:39.000
17 decimal points.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.000
Because way out there

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.000
in it-doesn't-matter-practically-

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:45.000
to-you land, most of the time,

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
out there in the

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
14, 15, 16, 17th

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
decimal point, you can see these numbers

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:53.000
are just a little

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.000
bit different. And that's because

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.000
floating point numbers are

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:59.000
an abstraction. They're not

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:01.000
literal point on the

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:03.000
number line like we were taught in

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:05.000
grade school about numbers.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:07.000
They're something different to make

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:09.000
it work in computers.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.000
And this is why

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.000
daddy drinks.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:15.000
And it's

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.000
things like this

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.000
that will drive you

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
insane. Because

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
even though most of us understand

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
this about floating point math,

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.000
I'll tell you a very quick

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:29.000
story about where I spent two

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:31.000
days with an engineer

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:33.000
last week,

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.000
then it was a floating point math problem.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:37.000
But it didn't come at us as

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:39.000
just value A equals value B.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:41.000
What we were doing was we were doing a bunch

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.000
of math, and then we rank

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:45.000
it. And

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.000
after we rank it,

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:49.000
we then say, okay,

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.000
I want the row number,

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.000
and we use a second

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:55.000
sorting number

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
to say, basically, if there's ties,

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:59.000
use this other value.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
Use this deterministic

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
number over here to break ties.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.000
Because we want all of our systems to be

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:07.000
deterministic, meaning that there's no random

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.000
number generation here, so every time I run

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.000
it, I want it to barf out

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.000
exactly the same answer. No swapping

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.000
values around, right? This is huge.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.000
It ingests like 5 billion

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:19.000
records and

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:21.000
barfs out 11 million

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:23.000
after a bunch of aggregations.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:25.000
And we were

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:27.000
finding we weren't getting deterministic

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:29.000
answers. Now, out of 11 million,

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:31.000
maybe we would have 30.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:33.000
That would change every run.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:35.000
And we were like, that's not cool. What's going on?

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:37.000
And as we dug into it,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:39.000
what we found is some of the

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.000
condition that should have been a tie

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.000
was like

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
this situation where

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.000
I was showing you where it's conceptually

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.000
the same number, but

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:51.000
they were flipping because, and the

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:53.000
reason it was happening is we were on Spark.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:55.000
Spark's a distributed system. You don't

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:57.000
control which executors

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:59.000
or how the groupings are done because

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.000
it's map-reduced. So every time

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.000
we ran it, and maybe we ran it with a different

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.000
cluster size, maybe one machine

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:07.000
got the data first,

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.000
little things change, and so

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
when we aggregated these up,

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:13.000
we'd get slightly different floating point rounding

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:15.000
because of the way they were grouped.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:17.000
And it became

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.000
material because of that sort order problem.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:21.000
We thought we were handling

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
ties with numbers, but we weren't.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:25.000
So, I mean, that was easy to solve,

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:27.000
right? We just round those

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.000
to some smaller number, you know, or

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
we cast them into something with

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.000
less precision, so we get

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:35.000
rid of that noise out in floating point land.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:37.000
You know, but we spent two of

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.000
our time for like, well, I think there's more

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.000
people than that involved, for like four days

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.000
trying to figure out why the hell these numbers keep changing,

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:45.000
right? Why is there a ghost in my machine?

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:47.000
Well, if you're interested in this, this isn't

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
a presentation about floating point numbers, even though

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:51.000
it may feel like it right now. I recommend

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.000
reading Julia Evans, you may

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:55.000
know her as Bork,

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:57.000
article about floating point

00:28:57.000 --> 00:28:59.000
numbers, and she does a number of

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.000
fantastic computer science-y

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:03.000
zines explaining

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:07.000
these concepts using

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:09.000
cartoons, and they're fantastic.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.000
And, you know, she points out

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
that doing numerical computations on a computer

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:15.000
inherently involves some approximation

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:17.000
and rounding, right? That's

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
one thing we should all come in this with knowing.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:21.000
All right.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:23.000
Enough of floating point math.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:25.000
I'm an agricultural economist. Let's talk

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.000
about silos.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
So, Cara mentioned

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
silos in

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:33.000
organizations, right?

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
And so let's think about using

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
our mindset of an abstraction, let's

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.000
think about silos for a minute.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:41.000
What are

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.000
if organizations

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:45.000
are abstractions, what's

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:47.000
the abstraction equivalent of

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:49.000
an organizational silo? And I

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.000
would say that's a over-

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:53.000
restrictive abstraction,

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:55.000
and it's an abstraction

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
that when it leaks, you can't

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:59.000
figure out why.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:01.000
So, let's think

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
what that, what org abstraction

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
leakage looked like. So,

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.000
where did this number in the

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:09.000
DB, in the database, where did it come from?

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:11.000
If your organization

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:13.000
is highly siloed, you may

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:15.000
not be able to answer that question if your team

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:17.000
didn't calculate it. That's an overly

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.000
rigid

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.000
abstraction.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:23.000
Who do I talk to about solving

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.000
this problem, whatever that

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:27.000
may be. If you can't answer that,

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.000
you've got a siloed organization, right?

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
It's overly rigid abstraction.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.000
And how was this decision

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:35.000
made, right? Non-

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:37.000
computational, right? It may just be like,

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:39.000
you know, we're making decisions

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:41.000
about people, we're making decisions

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:43.000
about a number of different things.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:45.000
How were they made?

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:47.000
Well,

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:49.000
the

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.000
general evidence of leaking

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:53.000
abstraction, what are those?

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:55.000
Now, these are like,

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:57.000
I went looking for, surely people have articulated

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.000
this, and I couldn't really find

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
any other authors or academic authors

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
who had really outlined this. I am sure

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:05.000
it's out there, and I am reinventing the wheel.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:07.000
But the thing I'm always looking for is

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.000
unexpected behavior,

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:11.000
uninterpretable

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
responses, or logical

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:15.000
errors where I,

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:17.000
there's no explanation.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:19.000
And whether that's my computer

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.000
or my organization,

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:23.000
there's no signs of slippage

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:25.000
or leakage in the abstractions.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.000
So, I think of a bunch of this as

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:29.000
really, in an organization, it's a communication

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.000
problem, and

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.000
communication is like beer.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:35.000
Communication is the source of and solution

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.000
to all our problems.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:39.000
So, you know, if you run into

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:41.000
where did this number in the DB come from,

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:43.000
there's ways that we can improve communication

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:45.000
in our organization to answer this, right?

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
We can have the code for the ETL

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.000
or whatever in version control,

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:51.000
so Git, GitHub, whatever version control you use,

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.000
and available

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
to the people in the organization who consume

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:57.000
the values, right? And that's really important

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.000
because a lot of organizations do

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:01.000
not share, read only is fine,

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:03.000
but they don't share the ETL

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.000
process for how they do things with the people

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:07.000
who are consuming those things. That's insanity!

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:09.000
Right? Like, we

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:11.000
can read code, many of us who are doing

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:13.000
things with the data, show us how it was calculated

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:15.000
because it may answer a whole bunch of questions

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:17.000
we have about what we're trying

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:19.000
to do. And, you know,

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.000
a wiki page describing the process

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:23.000
if there's a complicated

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:25.000
decision that's made in how we do

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.000
grouping, we always omit this,

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.000
we always include that, that sort of

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:31.000
stuff, put that junk in a wiki or documentation

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.000
that's easily accessible.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:35.000
So, similarly,

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
like the question, how do I talk about

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:39.000
solving this? Well, if everything

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:41.000
in the organization has clear ownership,

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.000
that one gets resolved really fast

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:45.000
because you talk to the owner of that process

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
or that system, and we often

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:49.000
let ownership slip and things get

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:51.000
orphaned, and then they just

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:53.000
leak, like, all over the

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.000
floor because there's no person

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:57.000
whose job it is to explain

00:32:57.000 --> 00:32:59.000
why it's leaking or help stop the leak

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:01.000
or help you understand what the

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:03.000
system is doing. And then

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.000
things like, how was this decision

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:07.000
made? Well, that's

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:09.000
better transparency,

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:11.000
leadership communication.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.000
Somebody didn't communicate how

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.000
the decision was made or what the process was.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:17.000
And a bunch of times, those are easily

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:19.000
solved by communication, and

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:21.000
probably, for big decisions,

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:23.000
they need to be communicated multiple

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:25.000
times in multiple ways on multiple

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:27.000
methods. So, a video,

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:29.000
an all-hands

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.000
call, an email.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:33.000
You know, one of the struggles

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.000
I have is people tend to act like

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.000
email is a reasonable way to access me

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.000
when they put me on BCC.

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:41.000
I don't read if I'm on BCC.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:43.000
The volume of email I get, I can barely

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:45.000
read the stuff that's got my name spelled right.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:47.000
And everything else

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
goes into a folder named, like,

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
BCC Read Later.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.000
Later.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.000
And I,

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:57.000
every once in a while, I miss

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.000
important internal corporate

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.000
communication because I wasn't paying

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:03.000
attention to that, but my email

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:05.000
volume is much more manageable.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.000
So, don't communicate

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.000
very important things to your

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
organization with them all on BCC.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.000
So, sometimes

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:15.000
we need multiple methods to

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.000
communicate to make sure the message isn't dropped.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:19.000
Alright, with that said,

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:21.000
that's a little bit about organizational

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
abstraction leakage and how we

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.000
might address that. I want to do a little

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:27.000
history, and it wouldn't be a data

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.000
science conference with an old man at the

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:31.000
front if we didn't put up

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:33.000
Drew Conway's Venn Diagram

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:35.000
from 2010.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:37.000
Now, funny story,

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.000
I knew Drew when he was a PhD

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:41.000
student at NYU, and

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:43.000
I saw him, like, draw this out

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.000
on a napkin, and it, like,

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.000
completely blew my brain when

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:49.000
five years later, like, the actuarial

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:51.000
magazines on my actuarial department

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.000
desk at work, like,

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.000
had this diagram on the cover. I'm like,

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:57.000
this is so weird. So, sometimes I

00:34:57.000 --> 00:34:59.000
feel like I'm the Forrest Gump of data science.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.000
It's like, I was sitting at the bar

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:03.000
when Drew Conway wrote this on a napkin, right?

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:05.000
I didn't actually do anything, but, you know, I saw it

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:07.000
go down.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.000
So, what's interesting about this,

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:11.000
and the reason I want to bring it up, is

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.000
the thing that was

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:15.000
so revolutionary about this

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:17.000
in 2010, inside of organizations,

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.000
is these are

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:21.000
three different abstractions.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:23.000
And they, one person was,

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:25.000
not only wasn't expected to do this,

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:27.000
one person in many organizations

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.000
was not allowed

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:31.000
to do this. I can

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:33.000
remember many times in the early

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.000
2000 being told, I couldn't

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:37.000
have coding tools on

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:39.000
my machine at work

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.000
because I was not a software

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:43.000
developer. And I'm like, I don't think you

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:45.000
understand what we're doing and what these tools are.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:47.000
Right? And it's like,

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:49.000
oh no, you're in the business. You get,

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:51.000
you know, Excel.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:53.000
And I'm like, I can

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:55.000
write code in VBA. You're not going to like

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.000
it. Why do I have to use the shitty

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.000
code when I could write

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:01.000
good code, and

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:03.000
you're just shunting me into that because

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.000
it's the abstraction you're comfortable with. It's not the

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.000
abstraction I'm comfortable with.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:09.000
And what happened since

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:11.000
then, so in only, you know,

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.000
13 years, is

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:15.000
it's now totally

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:17.000
acceptable, almost everywhere,

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:19.000
except a few backwards government

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
organizations, for people

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.000
who are doing like data science-y work

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.000
in the business, doing analytical

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.000
work, to have

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:29.000
first class programming tools

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.000
on their machine, and they have

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:33.000
rights and permissions to use those, and

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.000
often install packages, and even if

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:37.000
that's from a curated internal repo.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:39.000
But we can do these

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:41.000
things that 13 years ago we

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:43.000
were literally told we were not allowed

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:45.000
to do. That's a

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:47.000
fundamental change. And

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:49.000
I will assert that the single biggest

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.000
business value derived from the data

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:53.000
science movement in the last 13 years

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:55.000
is making it legitimate to

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:57.000
code outside of IT software development

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.000
roles. Now, that's a pretty big

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.000
assertion, right? A lot of value has come out

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:03.000
of data science. But this is

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:05.000
the, inside of these big

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
calcified organizations,

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:09.000
seeing all Drew Conway's

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:11.000
diagram inside of

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
magazines, and executives say,

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
well, how do we get that? And I look over their

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
shoulder and say, stop being stupid about

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.000
the rules of what we put on our desktop,

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:21.000
or give us access

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:23.000
to, you know, coding tools through a

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:25.000
JupyterLab, or through RStudio

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.000
that's centrally hosted. You know,

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.000
that opened up for these

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:31.000
tools to permeate across

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:33.000
organizations. And so

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:35.000
these data science roles break

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:37.000
previous organizational abstractions

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:39.000
is my point there, right?

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:41.000
I'll make a second

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
assertion, and it's tied

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:45.000
into what we talked about earlier.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.000
Abstractions will leak. Spolsky told

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:49.000
us that. Therefore, abstractions

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:51.000
must be permeable to allow

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:53.000
debugging. So that's

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:55.000
my thing of, put your

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:57.000
ETL code where everyone can read it

00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:59.000
who might be using the results of it.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:01.000
That's allowing us to at least

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:03.000
peek through the abstraction

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.000
and see what we're getting.

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:07.000
This holds for both organizations and

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.000
computers. So inside of

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:11.000
organizations, we need to understand

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.000
when those organizational structures leak,

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:15.000
how do we

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:17.000
deal, how do we peek

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.000
behind the layer of abstraction? Now, for

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:21.000
me, I've been in an organization,

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:23.000
the same organization for an

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.000
insane number of years. I've been at the same employer

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
for 14 years. I have had the same

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.000
boss for 12 years.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:31.000
My solution is easy. Because of that,

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.000
I start calling people, right?

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:35.000
Hey, what's going on with whatever? Or sending

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:37.000
them a text message. But my

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
analysts don't know who to contact.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.000
So I've got to be that to them.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.000
So I've got to go to them and ask questions of, hey,

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:45.000
do you guys understand what's happening? Do you understand

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.000
why? And then we talk.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:49.000
Okay, some of you may have had questions or thoughts

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:51.000
that you weren't comfortable bringing in the group.

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:53.000
Feel free to hit me up one-on-one.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:55.000
What I'm trying to do is

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:57.000
these things may be leaking for you.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:59.000
It's okay. Come to me. Talk about it.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:01.000
We'll deal with the leaks, and I'll help you understand

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.000
what's going on. And this is germane, because

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:05.000
we're right in the middle of acquiring another company.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:07.000
And there's lots of questions, right?

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:09.000
And some of it I have answers to, and some of it I don't.

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:11.000
But that's how we handle it.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.000
So there's leaky abstractions all the way

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
up and down your organization, and all the way up and down

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
our tech stacks. All right, my

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:19.000
assertion three.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:21.000
No single abstraction is right for everyone.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:23.000
I think we're going to need more

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:25.000
abstractions. Now, we have found

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:27.000
in our organization, and this is the part

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
where I'm going to share some things that's not

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.000
just my thoughts.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.000
My colleague,

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
John Moore, and Peter Ilston,

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.000
another one of my colleagues, came

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.000
up with what we call the 80-16-4.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:41.000
And it really started as the 80-20 rule,

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:43.000
and then we realized we needed to divide the 20

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.000
into two buckets, so we applied the

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:47.000
80-20 rule to the 20, and we got 80-16-4,

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:49.000
because math is fun.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:51.000
And we like non-Gaussian distributions,

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:53.000
given our world.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.000
So the way we think about everything we do

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
is 80% of

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
our users in our organization are

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:01.000
normal business users. Now,

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:03.000
I'm going to present all this from a for-profit

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
corporate organization. These should project

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:07.000
into your world, and don't,

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:09.000
even though I've got numbers up here,

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:11.000
don't be obsessed with

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:13.000
what that means. This is conceptual.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:15.000
The vast majority of your folks

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
are normal business users.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.000
They want to use applications,

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:21.000
dashboards, basic Excel.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.000
That's their tool stack. Those are their

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:25.000
abstractions. And then

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:27.000
16% or so

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:29.000
are super users.

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.000
Super users are going to want to do

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:33.000
SQL against the underlying

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:35.000
data that's collected by your tools.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.000
They may want to do a custom dashboard.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:39.000
They're going to do some advanced Excel,

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:41.000
like pivot tables, and really

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:43.000
processing the data a bit more.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:45.000
And then 4% are guru users.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:47.000
Your guru users are like,

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:49.000
oh, I want to do that, but I want to do

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:51.000
it 10,000 times, so can I hit the

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:53.000
API and just do that directly,

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.000
pull a result back, make a change,

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:57.000
put it in, run your thing,

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:59.000
pull it back? You know, that's a very

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:01.000
different use case. Or maybe they want a

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:03.000
library, a Python library, an R library

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:05.000
that interacts with your corporate tooling.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:07.000
Very different

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:09.000
abstractions needed by these

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:11.000
three different groups. And they're cumulative,

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:13.000
right? So the way I think about it is

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:15.000
your super users, they will use the

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:17.000
dashboards and the basic Excel,

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:19.000
but they also want these other things. Your guru

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
users are, of course, still using

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:23.000
SQL, right? And they're still using

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:25.000
your applications. They're using everything.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.000
This

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:29.000
has been

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:31.000
incredibly helpful for us

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:33.000
because what I had observed

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:35.000
in our organization

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:37.000
and in others is a tendency

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:39.000
to, like, scratch the 80%

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:41.000
itch and then

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:43.000
kind of stop

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:45.000
and make it hard to get the underlying

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:47.000
data. And we had had

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.000
at times in our culture where that wasn't the

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:51.000
case, and then as we started specializing

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:53.000
teams, some of this

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:55.000
16 and 4 was getting

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:57.000
dropped sometimes. So, you know, we've

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:59.000
changed kind of the definition of done

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:01.000
on the things we build, saying

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:03.000
we've got to make sure people from all three

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:05.000
of these groups agree

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:07.000
that they have what they need.

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.000
Now, it doesn't mean that everything

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:11.000
we do has an API, right? That's

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:13.000
not the principle. The principle is

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:15.000
what the people in that group

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:17.000
need, they have access to.

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:19.000
And I try to be real careful,

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:21.000
like, don't hear me saying, you know, build

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:23.000
APIs everywhere, because then all of

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:25.000
these, no, you're working backwards. Work from

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:27.000
the principle, not from the

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.000
implementation. We implement what we

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.000
need to address the principle.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:33.000
How do you know, like, what your guru

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:35.000
users need? We'll just make them an

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:37.000
API. No, you're going to go ask

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:39.000
them, right? Back to communication.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:41.000
And they may say, oh,

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
if I just have access to the output data

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.000
in SQL, that's more than

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:47.000
enough for me. Great.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.000
Don't build anything specifically

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:51.000
for them. This is

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:53.000
where, like, I really like the

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:55.000
current movement for data products,

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:57.000
because data products are used,

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
data product meaning, like, it's defined,

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.000
it's got a

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:03.000
data dictionary, it's not, like,

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:05.000
tied in necessarily to the whole corporate

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:07.000
database, but it's a

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:09.000
standalone data product, all the fields are

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
defined, and in our shop,

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:13.000
we have a link to a wiki page, and

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:15.000
a link to the source code that

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:17.000
builds that data product available for

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:19.000
everyone. I love that.

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:21.000
Like, even though when I first heard data product,

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:23.000
I thought it was, like, more marketing BS,

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.000
and I just wasn't excited about it,

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.000
when I saw what I got from it,

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:29.000
I'm like, oh yeah, data product, I want that.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:31.000
Because a whole bunch of my 16 and 4's

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:33.000
needs are addressed

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:35.000
by having a good data product, right?

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
Because it's a good abstraction that

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
we can peek behind, because of the

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:41.000
documentation and the links to the source code.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:43.000
So it's fantastic. So,

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:45.000
like, the point there is

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.000
multiple abstractions is a

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:49.000
high empathy move, right? I'm here with my

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:51.000
practice radical empathy shirt on.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:53.000
That's high empathy for

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:55.000
who's actually using it.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:57.000
Building APIs blindly because

00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:59.000
Gartner

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:01.000
says that's a good idea is not a high

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.000
empathy move, right?

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.000
That's just parroting, you know, what someone

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:07.000
you believe to be a thought leader. Don't do that.

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:09.000
Think. Right? Think about

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:11.000
what people actually need,

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.000
and build what they actually need.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:15.000
And more importantly, don't build stuff they don't need.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:17.000
And that's hugely

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:19.000
empathetic. So, my big

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:21.000
idea recap is

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:23.000
abstractions start way up with

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.000
leaders and go all the way down to

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:27.000
hardware. It's abstractions all the way up

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:29.000
and down. To debug an abstraction,

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:31.000
you have to see what's below it.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:33.000
We're building mental models of

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:35.000
complex systems, and that's why we

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.000
need abstractions, because we can't hold it all in our

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.000
head at once. You can't

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:41.000
master all abstractions.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.000
Decide if you're going to learn

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:45.000
or if you're going to partner,

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.000
but don't decide to blame the abstraction

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.000
you don't know. Ensure

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:51.000
an abstraction is for everyone.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:53.000
My metric for that is the 80-16-4,

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:55.000
but don't be dumb about it.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:57.000
And more importantly, just like Hadley helped me

00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:59.000
years ago on Stack Overflow,

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:01.000
help everyone kick ass, because

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:03.000
almost nobody really

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:05.000
wants to know how to code or do these things.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.000
We just want to solve some problem,

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.000
as Kara said. Or as I say,

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:11.000
we just want to kick ass. Right?

