The abstractions are so leaky.

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:05.000
How to know...

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:07.000
I think we should

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:09.000
always... This is some real Stephen

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:11.000
Covey seven steps of highly

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.000
effective people advice, but we need to

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.000
keep the end in mind. What

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.000
problem are we solving? The goal isn't

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.000
more abstractions. The goal

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.000
is compartmentalization

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.000
of concerns and the problem,

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:25.000
and if we're spending all of our time

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:27.000
redefining new abstractions because

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:29.000
we have an abstraction fetish,

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:31.000
that may not be healthy,

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:33.000
but it is a little bit gray sometimes

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.000
to know the right level abstractions, or if you

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:37.000
build an abstraction that's too compartmentalized...

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.000
I think one of the examples that's floating

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.000
around right now in the zeitgeist online

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:43.000
is the discussion of microservices

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:45.000
and how lots of companies,

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.000
the development teams, have looked at what Amazon

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:49.000
and Google do and are like,

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:51.000
oh yeah, everything has to be a microservice.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:53.000
What is a microservice but a very

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:55.000
specific abstraction, right?

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.000
They build thousands of these,

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.000
and they're not

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:01.000
Amazon, they're not Google, they don't

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:03.000
need that. That could have been solved

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.000
with a query, could have replaced five

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:07.000
microservices.

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.000
That's an example of losing

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:11.000
sight of the problem

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.000
and following the advice blindly

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:15.000
of microservices are good, or APIs

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:17.000
are good. So keep the end problem

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:19.000
in mind of what problem we're

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.000
actually going to try to solve.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:23.000
How's it going to be used?

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:25.000
One of the things I do is I love user personas,

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:27.000
and people in marketing use

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:29.000
user personas, and they're often quite vague.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:31.000
They'll be an imaginary person.

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.000
I've used this in other talks, but my favorite is

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.000
Ann Taylor, the woman's clothier.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:37.000
There is no person named Ann Taylor,

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:39.000
but you couldn't tell that inside of the

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:41.000
design meetings at Ann Taylor, because

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:43.000
she is a real person. She has a dog, dog has a name,

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:45.000
she has an address, she has a job.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:47.000
They completely

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:49.000
describe her, and that's

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:51.000
who they make clothes for.

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:53.000
Marketing does that because they don't know their customers,

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:55.000
so they create usually a few

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.000
different personas that they are targeting.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.000
I watch software development

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:01.000
teams inside of our organization.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:03.000
We've got under 1,000 people,

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:05.000
and I have sat in meetings

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:07.000
where they debated, what does this user

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:09.000
persona want from this?

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:11.000
I'm like, that's Robin.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
Call Robin and

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:15.000
ask him.

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:17.000
Why are we messing around with

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:19.000
dreaming up our...

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:21.000
Put a name on every user persona

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:23.000
if your organization is small,

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:25.000
and then ask that person,

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.000
is this solving your problem?

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:29.000
They may go yes, or they may go no,

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:31.000
so one way to stay out of that is make sure

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:33.000
what problem you're solving, who you're

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:35.000
solving it for, and ask them.

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.000
We've got a couple

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:39.000
of questions about the 80-16-4

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:41.000
role.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:43.000
The first one is,

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.000
how can we keep our empathy

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:47.000
for that 80% and protect

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
them, and how do we avoid them

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.000
from just being seen as these low-skilled,

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:53.000
low-status people,

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:55.000
the disposable post-docs

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:57.000
of academia?

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:59.000
It depends on your organization.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.000
In my shop,

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:03.000
I have empathy for them, but I don't

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:05.000
build most of my tools most of the time

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:07.000
are not for them.

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:09.000
They're using tools that put things into

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.000
systems, and I'm accessing it in the system.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.000
I want to

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:15.000
make sure that they're taken care of

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
by our software development team,

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
but they're not mine to take care

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:21.000
of. They need sets of tooling.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:23.000
In some ways, they may not

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:25.000
be your responsibility, depending

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:27.000
on how your organization is laid out. That's somebody else's

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:29.000
responsibility. If they're your responsibility,

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:31.000
you've got to figure out how to have

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:33.000
empathy for them and make the tooling they need,

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:35.000
but don't try to

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:37.000
make them a 16 or a 4. Don't try to

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:39.000
make them a power user or guru if they don't have any

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:41.000
interest in being. But if you get some of those

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:43.000
regular users, and we see this, we'll get users

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:45.000
that are like,

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:47.000
is it possible that I

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.000
could write a query to get this data out?

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:51.000
We're like, yeah, let's

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
talk about it. I can show you how to do that.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.000
We'll move people,

00:51:55.000 --> 00:51:57.000
but it isn't a career prerequisite

00:51:57.000 --> 00:51:59.000
that people be moving from the 80

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:01.000
to the 60. It's not a career path map.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:03.000
It's an organizational

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:05.000
structure. If you're responsible

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:07.000
for them, figure out how to love them.

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:09.000
If you're not responsible for them, eat lunch

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:11.000
with them so you understand their world,

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:13.000
but

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:15.000
I don't sit around worrying, are they

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:17.000
getting their needs met? That's somebody else's

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:19.000
job.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:21.000
You actually answered both of the questions.

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:23.000
Twofer. I like it.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:25.000
I had a question for you about some specific

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:27.000
metaphors of today and how you think

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:29.000
about them. I think the data warehouse,

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.000
the data lake,

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:33.000
and now the combination of the two,

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.000
which is the data lake house.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:37.000
Oh my god.

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:39.000
I have dropped so much

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:41.000
profanity mocking

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:43.000
this marketing language around

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:45.000
these things. Let me tell you

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:47.000
how I think

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:49.000
about it. The data

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:51.000
warehouse means

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:53.000
to me, or the way I assume

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:55.000
people mean, and I'm afraid people use

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:57.000
these differently.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:59.000
What it means to me is some

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:01.000
thought has been given to creating

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:03.000
fact tables and dimensions

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:05.000
and star or snowflake

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:07.000
schemas that cover multiple

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.000
areas of the business. It's usually a very

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:11.000
big lift to create a data

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:13.000
warehouse.

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:15.000
It takes a lot of top-down orchestration

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.000
to figure out the right granularity

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:19.000
of the data for your fact tables and

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
which things are dimensions and all

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:23.000
of this. It's a super

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:25.000
highly structured but really powerful,

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:27.000
but the problem becomes it's really

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:29.000
hard to get new stuff in because

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:31.000
it's a big change and you will never

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
change the granularity of it.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:35.000
Once that granularity, the grain

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:37.000
of the data,

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:39.000
it's not easy to change.

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:41.000
It can be done, but it will be

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:43.000
a big lift to do that.

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:45.000
It's going to be slower moving, but it's

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:47.000
super valuable.

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:49.000
The data

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:51.000
lake

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.000
approach is a little more

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:55.000
you've got a system that

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:57.000
squirts data out, capture it.

00:53:57.000 --> 00:53:59.000
It may be

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:01.000
logs, it may be some

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:03.000
sets of results. You're just accumulating

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.000
those in a way where they could be

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
queried later. Then data

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.000
lake house is like, let's

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:11.000
try to do a little bit of both all at once

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:13.000
and we're going to see,

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:15.000
and often what that means is you

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:17.000
create a bunch of ETL processes

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:19.000
in your data lake to extract

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:21.000
things that are interesting and drop them

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:23.000
in a schema where people can use them.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.000
That's usually what it is, is ETL

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.000
on top of your data lake.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:29.000
That's great.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:31.000
A lot of these are marketing terms

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:33.000
to try to get people to talk about it.

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:35.000
I'm back to what problem are you trying to solve?

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:37.000
If we understand

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:39.000
what problem we're going to solve,

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:41.000
it may be fine to do one

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.000
or it may be we need the other.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.000
Very few people are building

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:49.000
huge data warehouses

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:51.000
in my limited experience

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:53.000
because of this big cost

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:55.000
low agility feature.

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:57.000
Very slow to build

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:59.000
and they're very slow to change

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.000
and they're costly to build.

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:03.000
Because it spreads many parts of the organization,

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:05.000
everybody hates them fractionally

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:07.000
in their own special way.

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:10.000
I think that's part

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:12.000
and also storage has gotten so cheap.

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:14.000
We can just kind of forget

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:16.000
about dimension tables.

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:18.000
We just repeat our data

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.000
because we have columnar databases

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:22.000
so that's not near as costly

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:24.000
and storage is cheap.

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:26.000
We end up doing lots of big flat tables

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:28.000
stuck there that are useful.

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:30.000
We just think less

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:32.000
about data modeling

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:34.000
and you'll know when you're thinking

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:36.000
too little about data modeling

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:38.000
and you start sucking

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:40.000
and you're like maybe we should have

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:42.000
given some thought to data modeling

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:44.000
and you go back and do it

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:46.000
and we're all figuring this out

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:48.000
sort of emergently and organically.

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:50.000
Hope that answered.

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:52.000
I think we've got time for one last question.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:54.000
I'm not sure whether this is for you or for me

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:56.000
but I'm going to give it to you.

00:55:56.000 --> 00:55:58.000
How leaky do you consider something like dplyr?

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:00.000
I literally told Davis

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:02.000
at dinner two nights ago

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:04.000
that the thing I like about dplyr

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:06.000
is for SQL-like transformations.

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:08.000
So kind of the normal stuff

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:10.000
you might do with SQL.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:12.000
I consider dplyr

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.000
as like an appliance.

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:16.000
One of the definitions of an appliance

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:18.000
is it just does what it's supposed to do.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:20.000
You don't think about it.

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:22.000
You're dishwashing.

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:24.000
You don't think about how it works.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:26.000
It just works.

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:28.000
Dplyr for a lot of that sort of stuff

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:30.000
I think it's very unleaky.

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:32.000
I think if you start trying to do

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:34.000
data frames inside of data frames

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:36.000
or whatever that foolishness is you let people do

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:40.000
Those

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:42.000
probably leak

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:44.000
but I don't know because I don't do them.

00:56:44.000 --> 00:56:46.000
It's really good

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:48.000
for a bunch of stuff.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:50.000
You guys have slowly morphed it over time

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.000
like how you change the cast and melt

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:54.000
to the pivot longer, pivot wider.

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:56.000
That's been actually

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:58.000
that has taken leakiness away

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:00.000
and taken friction away.

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:02.000
You can change an API

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:04.000
but it's really helpful

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:06.000
in reducing leaks.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:08.000
I consider dplyr not particularly leaky.

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:10.000
What do you think about that?

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:12.000
How would you answer that?

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:14.000
The thing that I think about the most is dbplyr.

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:16.000
dbplyr leaks like a sieve.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:18.000
Yeah.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:20.000
We are trying to translate

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:22.000
our code to SQL.

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:24.000
Yes, it leaks at some level.

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:26.000
It leaks like a sieve

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:28.000
but amazingly it works.

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:30.000
Yeah.

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:32.000
I think the thing that's most surprising to me

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:34.000
is most of the stuff you're trying to do to data

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:36.000
like filtering and aggregation

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:38.000
you can do it in R,

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:40.000
you can do it in JavaScript, you can do it in SQL,

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:42.000
you can do it in Python.

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:44.000
It's all basically the same

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:46.000
and we can translate between that

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:48.000
with pretty high fidelity.

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:50.000
That's pretty surprising.

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:52.000
It really is kind of surprising.

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:54.000
Where it leaks is kind of akin to how SQL leaks

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:56.000
in that you start accumulating

00:57:56.000 --> 00:57:58.000
the steps and then at some point

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:00.000
you get unexpected behavior.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:02.000
That's not unique to dbplyr.

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:04.000
That's a little bit of the underlying SQL.

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:06.000
I have the same problem in SQL.

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:08.000
Then you have a permeating the membrane problem

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:10.000
because at some point

00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:12.000
you go, fine, dump the query out.

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:14.000
I dump the query out and you say,

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:16.000
oh God, what have I done?

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:18.000
I have my DBAs tell me

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:20.000
I can tell when you're doing a db query

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:22.000
because it's got really crazy SQL

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:24.000
that no one would write.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:26.000
So when it comes time

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:28.000
to solve some of those problems,

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:30.000
some of them aren't yours,

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:32.000
some of them are SQL,

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:34.000
but it can be a little tricky.

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:36.000
It's harder.

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:38.000
Yeah, that makes me think a fun talk would be.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:40.000
We could spend probably 30 minutes

00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:42.000
just talking about how leaky and abstraction SQL is.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:44.000
Oh, we really could.

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:46.000
I was tempted to jump into that,

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:48.000
but I was like, no, I want a super succinct example

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:50.000
and floating point was just so succinct.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:52.000
Thank you all very much.

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:54.000
Thank you.

